
[1]proclivity

   PROCLIV'ITY, n. [L. proclivitas, proclivis; pro and clivus, a cliff.]

   1. Inclination; propensity; proneness; tendency.

   The sensitive appetite may engender a proclivity to steal, but not a
   necessity to steal.

   2. Readiness; facility of learning.

   He had such a dexterous proclivity, that his teachers were fain to
   restrain his forwardness.
